A BeginEndBlock can enclose any statement. Some statements must be enclosed in curly braces `{}` instead of `begin-end`, 
and some must use `begin` and `end`. Here are the guidelines:
* Statements that do not affect the scope should use curly braces, such as a print statement. For example:
```
{print i;}
```
* Statements that modify variables or objects within a scope should use `begin-end`, and any subsequent statements 
inside the block can access the modified variable or object. For example:
```
int i = 0;
begin
   //Modify variable inside begin-end block
   i++;
end
print i;
```
* If a statement needs to access two variables that were declared outside of it, then use curly braces because the 
variable scope is restricted. For example:
```
int j = 0;
begin
   //Modify variable inside begin-end block
   j++;
   print i;
   print j;
   //The statement below would not have access to the variable outside of the block, so use curly braces instead.
   {print ++i;}
end
```

